text:
kapustin sonata 1, op 39
‚Äî
first sonata of the 20 or so this genius wrote. although the sonata-fantasia op. 39 was only the fourth composition by kapustin for solo piano, its structure appears quite mature already. this piece consists of four movements in different jazz styles, with the first three movements being played without interruption.

the movement presented in this clip, the first, is characterized by a long, virtuositic passage that encompasses the entire movement practically. a gorgeous, kaspustin-style melody comes out in the midst of the madness and is retold sparingly throughout the movement. truly remarkable piece.
.
.
.

i've lost a lot this year. not only good, but also the bad. moments that i will like to forget, and some i might like to relive. made memories with the same old people. walked the walk. let go of people who were toxic to my life. this new year, i would like you all to leave what hurt you behind and carry on with all the good; something new, something special. if you are reading this now, i want you to know that i am proud of you, for all your patience and bravery... for making through another year so gracefully. i know it's not hard, but darling, you are an icon. a shining star. people will talk shit, but you do you. it won't be easy, but it's not impossible. check on your loved ones, are they alright? with people coming closer virtually, but farther in reality, you never know who's hurting. take care and be nice. this year should all be what people were preaching in 2018, but were conflicted in their own opinion. as much as it sounds cheesy, but you're not alone. i'm here, all of the people who love you are here... it's just one little call, one little shout and a life could be saved. .
.
// ayesha fatimah .

‚†Ä
journaliste kate shellnutt was erbij. 'ik dacht direct: o nee, hij moet zijn aftreden bekend maken.'‚†Ä
‚†Ä
vrouwen die met hybels samenwerkten, beschuldigen hem van grensoverschrijdend gedrag. shellnutt vindt de zaak een belangrijke les voor de kerk in amerika. een voorganger die zo veel fans heeft en zo geliefd is, beschuldig je niet zomaar. 'het vraagt moed om dan je verhaal te doen.'‚†Ä
‚†Ä

text:
here i am, sat at my desk because this day calls for a spot of reflection. 2018, you‚Äôve been a real one. i‚Äôve had ups and downs, just like everybody else. politically, it‚Äôs been a mad one. the #metoo movement has continued to grow and tough conversations are finally being had, women are starting to be listened to and given a voice. we still have miles to go but it‚Äôs a strong starting point.
then there‚Äôs #brexit still unclear what‚Äôs going on there but in 2019 i hope we can all listen to each other, communicate better and understand that we are not enemies, even though our opinions may differ. 
personally, this year my friendships have grown stronger, i‚Äôve partied my lil socks off and i‚Äôve worked bloody hard with uni. i started @yapmagonline and i‚Äôm really excited to see how we grow and create on our very own platform (u know, after uni deadlines)

it‚Äôs also been a struggle though, i‚Äôve learned that my fear and lack of confidence in what i can do has been holding me back in a big way and in 2019 i hope to make every effort to stop that. i‚Äôve learned that i rely on other people far too much for my own sense of fulfilment and happiness and again, i hope to make steps to rectify that (tips welcome). i also want to eat more vegetables because oh my god i‚Äôm the least healthy person i know. 
i hope everyone has a fun and safe new years, let‚Äôs look forward to the future...i‚Äôll be working in a bar so pray for me! ‚ú®
.
.
.
.
.

text:
just want to post about this to bring awareness to the fact that animal abuse is more common than you might think and it all too often goes unreported. here‚Äôs my baby boat‚Äôs story, for those of you who don‚Äôt know. 
i adopted him because i went to freaking petsmart for some toys for my mom‚Äôs dog and they had the audacity to have an adoption sale of clearly abused kittens. so i got the sickest one and nursed him back to health. he got the name boat because even after all he had been through and even though he was such a sick baby, he always purred so loudly that it sounded like a motor boat üòÇ. sadly, my mom‚Äôs boyfriend killed him when he was only 8, back in 2013 while i was in rehab, and my mom didn‚Äôt tell me he was gone for three weeks. i felt horrible having to leave him with them at all, but i needed help and had to leave him somewhere. i thought my mom would protect him... i still feel responsible. rip baby boy... i hope he didn‚Äôt suffer. i loved him with my whole heart. here‚Äôs a picture of me and him from 2011.

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base. and if politics and government are just another game with winners and losers, then why not boo and threaten democrats as if they were duke basketball fans?

david karpf
medium

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
simone biles talks anxiety & being named 2018‚Äôs ‚Äòmost dominant athlete‚Äô

simone biles has been a force to be reckoned with since winning three consecutive world all-around titles in 2015, becoming‚Ä¶ ¬†gymnast simone biles appears on "good morning america," dec. 11, 2018.

simone biles¬†has been a force to be reckoned with since¬†winning three consecutive world all-around titles in 2015,¬†becoming the first female gymnast to do so. she has since continued to leave her mark on the world of gymnastics even after revealing she was sexually abused by former sports doctor larry nassar.

in an interview with¬†good morning america‚Äôs robin roberts, the athlete opened up about the anxiety caused by the deeply personal revelation as well as her journey to being dubbed 2018‚Äôs most dominant athlete by espn magazine.

when it comes to keeping her mental health in order, biles revealed that she takes anti-anxiety medication and speaks with a counselor regularly. ‚Äúi‚Äôm on anxiety medicine now because i had a lot of ups and downs throughout the year and trying to figure out what was wrong,‚Äù biles said tuesday. ‚Äúi go to therapy pretty regularly. it‚Äôs not easy but the people surrounding me are some of the best so it makes it a little easier.‚Äù ‚Äúi‚Äôve felt a bit broken and the more i try to shut off the voice in my head the louder it screams,‚Äù biles wrote on twitter in january, with the hashtag #metoo. ‚Äúi am not afraid to tell my story anymore.‚Äù

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in 2018, i set out from the safe harbour of a full-time job looking for adventures on the stormy  seas of disrupted journalism. 
i found those adventures in the most surprising of places: meshing design thinking and the opportunity of #metoo in nepal and lisbon; working with media innovators in australia and around the world as they refocus on their audience, not their advertisers, on their niche, not the mass; mapping the new media eco-system (watch this space in early 2019!). and i found time to write again.

i found new communities and wonderful teams as a senior fellow at the centre for media transition at uts, as a resident fellow at the house of beautiful business and as strategic designer in asia for splice media. 
i continued to be rewarded by the ever growing network of friends and allies that's the gift of being a jsk stanford fellow ('16) and as the founding ceo of the walkley foundation and founding director of the international federation of journalists asia pacific. 
and 2019? look out for the innovators map, for splice beta in chiang mai, for live journalism and for more adventures that are just starting to germinate!  #2018 #ohyes #thepowerofyes #lifeadventure #journalism #designyourlife #adventure
name: Jacqui Park

text:
as women we can probably never stop saying #metoo and it may take another decade (hopefully not) for us to get away from this vicious cycle. more often than not our sexual offenders are people who are close to us. why does this happen? these are people who might be your friends, members of a extended family or acquaintances.
.

i feel women have a sense of invisible guard up when they are around unknown people; which to some extent helps them from falling prey to sexual predators. but when we are surrounded by people whom we trust, we become defenseless.
.

there are times where you are in a shock about what happened and don't know how to react at that moment. some of you may agree with me and some may not. you remain silent and say nothing but some men take it as a sign of approval. .

men don't understand that during that time, there is a barrage of thoughts rushing through our minds like ‚Äòdid he just do that?‚Äô, ‚Äòno it can't be‚Äô, ‚Äòmaybe i am thinking too much‚Äô, 'did he just brush against me in the wrong way?‚Äô, 'i know him, he doesn't seem like a guy who will do that‚Äô and many more. as you start analyzing gradually and connect your thoughts properly you realize that yes you have been sexually assaulted in some way. that moment of realization makes you feel extremely disgusted and you think 'why me?‚Äô .
.
*continued to the next post.* #believewomen #belivesurvivors #whyididtreport #womensreality #timesup #imwithher #everydaysexism #tothegirls #heforshe #yesallwomen #fem2 #sexualassault

text:
it's strange the amount courage it took for me to go out get my first lgbtq+ novel. it's such an innocent thing. the discrimination in our society is so prevalent that reading a book or going out on a simple date with a woman (gasp!), can evoke such a strong fear response in my body. 
being different has been imprinted in my psyche as something that brings about negative consequences. i was bullied as a kid. i've done everything in my power to stay hidden and small so i never have to face the pain of being publicly rejected. 
what i've learned from hiding is that it does nothing but cripple my spirit. i can't do much with my life so long as hide. at least, not much that i'm truly and deeply proud of. 
i feel as though i'm nose diving off a cliff as share what is on my mind. my anxiety is skyrocketing, i'm scared shitless. even though i came out over year ago, i still feel like i'm coming out of hiding in every area of my life. everything that makes me who i am has been hidden. 
in a way, i feel like i'm getting to know myself for the first time. because of the power of yoga and meditation, i'm coming to place where i can feel my self love expanding. as it expands, i feel my shame beginning to fade. i believe 2019 will be a big year for me. i will encounter a lot that i've never experienced. i've had moments where i felt free, but i've never truly felt unleashed.
i have, for as long as i can remember, felt trapped in my own body. since i was a little girl, i felt like i was screaming and no one could hear me. not many people know this about me. some might question if i'm exaggerating. i'm not. this is my story. some don't understand because they know my family. this is not a reflection of my parents. this is a reflection of the human psyche and what happens to the brain as it struggles to process trauma. being bullied is a huge trauma for a child to process. i've carried this with me since the first grade. i've always needed to talk about it, but never really felt that i could. 
in spite of what i've been though, i feel like i'm finally coming home. it feels amazing. if you or someone you know is hurting, always seek out someone to talk to. 
#metoo

in a way, i feel like i am getting to know myself for the first time. because of the power of yoga and meditation, i am coming to place where i can feel my self love expanding. as it expands, i feel my shame beginning to fade. i believe 2019 will be a big year for me. i will encounter a lot that i have never experienced. i have had moments where i felt free, but i have never truly felt unleashed.
i have, for as long as i can remember, felt trapped in my own body. since i was a little girl, i felt like i was screaming and no one could hear me. not many people know this about me. some might question if i am exaggerating. i am not. this is my story. some do not understand because they know my family. this is not a reflection of my parents. this is a reflection of the human psyche and what happens to the brain as it struggles to process trauma. being bullied is a huge trauma for a child to process. i have carried this with me since the first grade. i have always needed to talk about it, but never really felt that i could. 
in spite of what i have been though, i feel like i am finally coming home. it feels amazing. if you or someone you know is huing, always seek out someone to talk to.

text:
a look back at 2018

the me too movement.

a cry against sexual assault and harassment in the workplace, the movement which had already gained widespread recognition in the west, started gaining momentum in our nation.

in a society like ours, where even reporting a sexual harassment incidence is deemed a taboo, let alone protesting against it, the way these valorous women have come forward to share their stories, expressing their anger and disgust, deserves applause. 
none were spared, be it top officials, politicians, or actors, thus highlighting that gone are the days when money and power could soften voices. and commendable is our country's spirit too,  we have perhaps learnt to hear women out without any judgmental glances. and not only are we listening to them now, we are willing to punish the guilty ( in the film industry, a number of accused have been made to back off from their current films).
and why not? what good is nation a where daughters cannot even expect something as basic as being employed safely?

to all the young girls and women reading this, there hasn't been a better time to raise your voice against the depraved monsters that walk among us. it's our time, and we deserve to work, and live with dignity, without any compromise at all.

there is still a long way to go and a lot of lessons that we, as a country, have to learn. but what gives one a glimmer of hope is that this year, we showed the world and we showed our women that we are willing to take a step in the right direction. we are willing to admit our wrongs and are willing to right them.

text:
we‚Äôre counting down the final hours of 2018 and finding many reasons to count the wins for women and girls of the world this year. .

this was the year that saw: ‚ûñwomen across the world unite, stand up and rise to the #metoo and #timesup movements ‚úîÔ∏è
‚ûñan unprecedented number of women speaking out and stepping up to catalyse record-breaking political races and social change ‚úîÔ∏è
‚ûña series of historic firsts including #spain appointing a majority-women cabinet ‚úîÔ∏è
‚ûñvoters in ireland striking down one of the most draconian #abortion bans in the developed world ‚úîÔ∏è
‚ûñwomen in saudi arabia able to drive legally ‚úîÔ∏è
‚ûñfemale candidates breaking historic ground in the us midterm elections and @michelleobama findjng her powerful voice‚úîÔ∏è
‚ûñiranian women watching the #worldcup in a sports stadium alongside men for the first time ‚úîÔ∏è
‚ûñnew zealand prime minister #jacindaardern making history as the second elected head of state to give birth while in office, and first elected leader ever to take maternity leave proving it is indeed possible to be both a prime minister and mum ‚úîÔ∏è‚úîÔ∏è
‚ûñthe #nobelpeace prize awarded jointly to denis mukwege, a congolese surgeon who treats rape victims, and nadia murad, an iraqi woman and member of the yazidi religious minority who was captured by isis and is now an activist advocating for victims of sex trafficking, and the first iraqi woman to receive the award ‚úîÔ∏è .
‚ûñ and among countless other extraordinary ordinary moments of women and girls standing up, stepping up and speaking out, without knowing it possibly, without claiming it, so they too, have advanced the causes, opportunities and rights of all women and girls, so in their honour, we @girledworld would like to thank them and thank you for being part of what made our 2018 rock, and leave you with the powerful wisdom of @drmayaangelou to give you fuel for 2019. .

may 2019 be the year of your becoming üëäüèΩ
#nye2019 #girledworld .
.

text:
hello everyone. 
it's really hard for me to pick the best moments of 2018, but i think i will give it a go! 
1. january 4th, 2018 i started hrt for my transgender journey. this was a long road of self discovery, and patience waiting to be stable enough to start hrt! 
2. april 17th, i celebrated my 21st birthday! which was a big milestones considering psychiatrists told my mom i would be dead from suicide or institutionalized. i also stopped my antipsychotic, and was completely off all antipsychotic medication, the first time sense i was a kid! this was freeing, because i didnt have a psychotic disorder.
3. august 4th i got married!!! which was so amazing, and beautiful. i never thought i could be with someone who i loved that much! i never thought i would say i do! but i did! 
4. november 28 i celebrated being out of the psychiatric hospital for two years, which was incredible for me! (first time sense i was 12)
5. in november i was told i most definitely did not have schizophrenia or any psychotic disorder, but a dissociative disorder.
6. december 7th i met my top surgeon and set up my surgery date!
--
although this year was hard, and full of many difficult times. there were times i was left feeling so hopeless, confused, angry, and upset. it was an amazing year. it was hard for me to remember that, just because i was our of the hospital for 2 years, didnt mean that my mental health journey stopped.

text: thank you 2018. being an artist is an exercise in pursuing the fight to imagine new realities while resisting the evidence that surrounds you suggesting change is impossible. it is painful and uncomfortable and absolutely worth it. to the people i painted in 2018; you will never know truly the depth of admiration i have for each of you. your trust and willingness to share yourself defiantly restores my faith in humanity in a time when its tempting to believe nothing matters. all that is grim is exploding but doesnt stand a chance in the face of the wealth of  power that brims from the hearts & minds of women & femme artists & healers. in 2018 amid long bouts of darkness, this truth rang clearest. 2019, im committed to the deeper dig, the longer path and fanning the flames of our collective ungovernable imagination. #nowallnoban #decolonizenow #ftp #prisonsdontwork #blacklivesmatter #artheals #fuckthepolice #metoo #youthvoicesmatter #nojusticenopeace #didisayfuckthepolice

text:
s t o p // you can stop apologizing now 
#advocate #idaho‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
what it means when you can‚Äôt stop saying ‚Äòi‚Äôm sorry‚Äô after escaping abuse.
heartfelt apologies can go a long way. ‚Äúi‚Äôm sorry what i said hurt your feelings.‚Äù
polite apologies make us decent human beings. ‚Äúi‚Äôm sorry i was late to our meeting!‚Äù
but repetitive, nearly constant apologies for every little thing ‚Äî or, what psychologist paige carambio, psyd calls, ‚Äúapologizing for existing‚Äù ‚Äî can actually be an after-effect of trauma, a self-preservation technique survivors may think they still need to utilize in order to protect themselves.
‚Äúit goes back to the first stage of being with an abuser, when the abuser is doing everything he or she can to tear the person down and make them feel completely worthless,‚Äù says carambio, who works with survivors of domestic abuse in beverly, mass. she says that hearing verbal derogation day-in and day-out can cause you to internalize those messages. what carries over, even after leaving the abuser, is this feeling that you need to apologize for every little thing, especially with a new partner, says carambio.

text:
if you take a piece of rotten fruit and place it beside perfectly good fruit...what happens?

the mold from the rotten fruit spreads over to the good fruit and both end up in bad condition.

so what happens when you surround yourself with people who are negative? well....you become just like them... ‚Äúyou are the average of the five people you spend the most time with.‚Äù - jim rohn

surround yourself with people who provide value in your life. not those who try to bring you down. for those are not good people.

text:
in 2018:
i moved 
drove on the highway for the first time since my car accident back in 2014.
spent half the year in and out of hospitals for different reasons. i had heart problems,my brother( tore his acl), mom (cancer treatments/tumor removal) and father ( hernia surgery, heart procedure)
my mom beat cancer.
i got fired.
readjusted, got certified and started a new career.
went back to school *masters degree pending*
left a relationship i thought i would be in for the rest of my life. 
noticed a lot of my wounds were self inflicted and began to patch myself. 
realized i have toxic behaviors myself that need to be purified.
made new friends.
saved 2 lives
learned the beauty of being plant based. 
was sexually assaulted twice and realized how important it is to speak up.

thank you 2018 everyday was a work in progress. when i first thought about it, i thought 2018 was shit. but i overcame so much. 2019 i expect you to be no different. uphill battles always.
#women #womenempowerment #visionboard #progression #lifehack #metoo #fuckcancer #hospitals #heartbreak #strength #perserverance #love #hope #friendship

text:
man alive what a year!!!! this has been one of the best years i've had to date. yes we have had many challenges to face and work through, but there has been so many amazing experiences, transformations, firsts, and memories being made. firstly i would like to say a huge thank you to those that have been a huge part of our life, that have helped, cared and supported us through, i definitely would not have made it without you all. this year i began a whole new journey on taking back my life, choosing happiness, and dealing with things in a different light. i have walked away from things that haven't served me, and made so many positive changes. this year i started this thing called a happy 100 that was introduced to me, and i am so proud to say that just hours away from the clock ticking over into the new year i completed 96/100 of them. i got my first car, i got my restricted licence, i am 1 year sober and smoke free, i've been to 20 waterfalls, saw pink in concert with my best friend and tara, i saw katy perry live, and went on so many adventures with my mini me, only 21000kms in 9 months hehe and of course rusty joined our family unit. i completed another year at university, and i left my job to fully support my girl with all the challenges she deals with on a daily basis. the whole point of the happy 100 is that happiness is a choice, instead of writing new years resolutions which let's be honest how many people actually stick to, writing down 100 things that will make you happy, it's also about personal accountability for your own happiness, through the choices you make. so for my last post of the year i wish you all a safe and happy new year, make good choices, and i'll see you on the other side xx

text:
here stood a beautiful photo.

it had nothing to with how i looked, the colour of my skin, the shape of my body,...it was beautiful because of the inner journey i went through to be at this present moment.

the pain, the suffering, the agony, the loss, the injustice, the solitude, the self sabotage, the self abuse, the mind control, the hatred, the black spew that shot through my veins and of which i spewed out onto the ground.

that which nature took in her in her embrace and that which made me become whole.

if it was a person that reported this beautiful image than i forgive you; for the inner pain you feel on a daily basis.  for the voice that tells you that you are not good enough.  because you are.  you are a goddess and a god and you deserve happiness.

to @instagram, who deleted this beautiful post of my journey.  who only saw a body in front of them who was not sexualized.  a body that was made of darkness and light.  a body which is a vessel for a beautiful soul that made it to the other side; to only be covered in light.

#instagramdeleted #dontdeleteartwork  #myjourneytohappiness #lettherebelight #injustice #metoo #journeyintothelight #witchesofinstagram #tantra #witchhunt

text:
have you ever made a vision board?  i admit, i used to think they were very hokey!  however, i began making vision boards 2 or 3 years ago and, i like them!

a vision board is a good way to conceptualize your hopes, dreams, and goals.  i like to make one at the beginning of the year.  i then keep it in my view so i can remind myself of my hopes, dreams, and goals for the year.  this is really great if you are a visual person!  it is also fun to see how things worked out at the end of the year.

how to make a vision board ‚Ä¢buy a poster board (many types and sizes) ‚Ä¢if you don‚Äôt get a poster board that has self-adhesive on it, you will need glue or tape. ‚Ä¢get a bunch of magazines.  turn off your filter and rip or cut out words, sayings, or pictures that catch your eye.  don‚Äôt overthink the ‚Äúwhy‚Äù part - just go with your heart‚Äôs desire. ‚Ä¢once done with the magazines, trim your pics/words/saying and think about how you want to arrange it on your board. ‚Ä¢put your finished board in a place where you can see it often. ‚Ä¢enjoy! üíú
name: Denise Styer, PsyD

text: did my hair. wore a girl power t-shirt that @ruackerman gave me. got headshots by a famous lady photographer, @heathersten. went to @sohohousela. met a baby zebra with @airbnb experiences and @animasarah. celebrated the first anniversary of the #resist tattoo i got at the @womensmarch. taught, briefly, at @columbia. contemplated #metoo and #brettkavanuagh. and celebrated a book and a person at the @guggenheim with karaoke and the #resistancerevivalchorus thanks to the wonderful @nespector, @tinder, @goodpeoples & my fantastic team @greyhorsecomms. it was an absolutely wild 2018 full of up down and sideways endeavors. #2018bestnine

this year, men were pushed further back into the doghouse because of guys like brett kavanaugh, les moonves and the like.  most of us guys aren‚Äôt bad but instead of making exceptions we‚Äôre all lumped together and made to be viewed as bad, dangerous and creepy.  with the birth of the #metoo movement, shaming men has become a frequent occurrence in 2018.  something that men should never feel bad for or have to apologize is just #beingmale.  we have feelings too even though society tells us we can‚Äôt show them too often.  it hurts when you hit us, i don‚Äôt care how big the guy is...pain is pain.  boys and men are falling behind in academia because more focus is not tending to the needs of male students which causes estrangement, depression, anxiety, among other things.  instead of making this argument an us vs. them approach, we should learn from each other‚Äôs experiences and try to help each other.  just remember that behind every strong man is a scared little boy trying to hold everything together because again, society tells us not to appear as weak.  that would totally kill us.  ladies, instead of working against us, work with us.

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
it bewilders me everytime why marx isn't counted amongst the great composers of the 20th century.  in his long life time he was awarded and honored many times and admired by almost all his peers. it's a damn shame. 
in writing his piano concerto in e major he said, "in this time of dry intellectualism, which unfortunately has also infected the holy kingdom of art with its destructive poison, it takes courage to go public with a romantic piano concerto, paying homage to beauty ideals of times bygone while ignoring the haughty laughter of the new musical devil-worshipers with their admiration for all sounds ugly." and this gorgeous concerto was born. take a listen why don't cha? .
.

.
.

text:
more than a dozen catholic and protestant feminist theologians have rewritten key passages in the bible that they believe had been misinterpreted or edited, to create what they say is a more faithful and up-to-date scripture text.
‚Äúwhile some say that you have to throw out the bible to be a feminist, we believe the opposite,‚Äù elisabeth parmentier, one of the authors of the project, called a women‚Äôs bible, told afp.
the idea was born at the university of geneva, itself once a hotbed of religious reformation, as the adopted home of john calvin, but the authors say they were inspired by a more recent effort. in the late 19th century radical suffragettes produced ‚Äòthe woman‚Äôs bible‚Äô, a controversial text that similarly challenged what the authors felt were diminished roles given to women in the english-language holy book.

for the current effort, which was published in french in october, the academics say that they have taken full advantage of the latest bible scholarship, to remove ‚Äúthe lingering patriarchal readings that have justified numerous restrictions and bans on women‚Äù as well as outright mistranslations.

one example is the well-known passage in the gospel of luke, in which jesus and the apostles visit the household of two sisters, mary and martha. in the story, mary is praised by jesus for listening to him at his feet, over her sibling, who is too preoccupied with preparing the house for the guests.
‚Äúit says that martha ensures the ‚Äòservice‚Äô, which has been interpreted to mean that she served the food, but the greek word diakonia can also have other meanings, for instance it could mean she was a deacon,‚Äù said parmentier.
another quest has been rescuing mary magdalene, the most-named woman in the gospels, from centuries of inaccurate readings and embellishments that have cast her as a fallen woman or prostitute. ‚Äúshe stood by jesus, including as he was dying on the cross, when all of the male disciples were afraid. she was the first one to go to his tomb and to discover his resurrection,‚Äù says parmentier.

‚Äúwhile some say that you have to throw out the bible to be a feminist, we believe the opposite,‚Äù elisabeth parmentier, one of the authors of the project, called a women‚Äôs bible, told afp.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: ‚Äúwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.‚Äù documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers‚Äô facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook‚Äôs ‚Äúplatform policy‚Äù allowed only collection of friends‚Äô data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook‚Äôs role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate ‚Äúinformation warfare‚Äù against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: ‚Äúwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.‚Äù documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers‚Äô facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook‚Äôs ‚Äúplatform policy‚Äù allowed only collection of friends‚Äô data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook‚Äôs role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate ‚Äúinformation warfare‚Äù against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers‚Äô facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook‚Äôs ‚Äúplatform policy‚Äù allowed only collection of friends‚Äô data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for adveising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook‚Äôs role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robe mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate ‚Äúinformation warfare‚Äù against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
breaking news: there are more types of candy apples here than a candy-apple-lovin‚Äô girl like me could ever eat. 
that‚Äôs right, my current events have been happily taking place in orlando, florida. first at universal studios, then disney, then my little family‚Äôs first trip to animal kingdom, which inspires me to share this fascinating bit... the females of our closest animal relatives, the bonobo, #cometogether to keep their community safe. they do their best to avoid aggression, practice #empathy, hug often, and, when a male in their group demonstrates violence, they team up to do what they must: oust him. 
this moves me. honestly, it fills my eyes with tears and my #heart with #hope. 
if we‚Äôve ever spoken, i‚Äôve probably shared my unabashed loyalty to a book called #thegiftoffear, which reminds us that we too possess animal instincts that serve to protect us. its author, an internationally-recognized safety expert who often speaks on #abuse, asks us to ignore the rules of polite society if it‚Äôs what it takes to #stopdomesticviolence. he directs us to speak up, to fight back, to save each other. he says these crimes are predictable and preventable given that they occur ‚Äúafter many warning signs, and after several people are aware of the risk.‚Äù his is a call not to be those people, made aware and *still* allowing ourselves to be prey. 
i will never be prey. never again. on the contrary, to this particular apple in my view, in the view of my sisters, i say‚Äì‚Äì chomp.

text: i'm very hard on myself so if you ask me i'd say i haven't had a good year since 2016 (i know everybody hates that year lol but i booked my first 2 costar roles in barry and the deuce, put up my solo show, and got nominated for an audelco). so in my eyes i haven't topped that but 2018 was pretty solid. i was 1 of the 50 black women playwrights selected out of over 200 to have my monologue about the #metoo movement performed in 50in50 at the billie holiday theater. i had my face all over buses, trains, and stations in my first print ad for #hivprep #livingsure. had the best 10 days ever in my first trip to california. from the pool to the mountain climbing i loved it! i launched afro goddess productions! i wrote, edited, and starred in my short film "razor pains" which got into a few festivals/screenings including katra film series. got to play the role of nilene cooper with an amazing cast/crew and director in "you wouldn't expect". got a new manager! and last but not least finished the proof of concept for "#undercoversidechick" written and starring myself with another fabulous crew and director! this was only my top moments! between roommate drama, landlord drama, moving twice, annoying days jobs, and my crazy love life i believe i did okay lol. so blessed to be a creative surrounded by other creatives with the support of family and friends who love me. its getting closer and closer to my 10 year anniversary in nyc and i feel like i'm only getting started! i love the life i live! #bestof2018

i don‚Äôt have time to make this post pretty or appealing, as yet again i‚Äôm sitting in public trying to focus on work and i am once again on the verge of bursting into tears - all i can think about is how none of my friends understand the situation i‚Äôm in and i have barely talked to any of them about this, because even when i first talked to them about this dilemma, i felt so judged. i‚Äôve withdrawn, not even reaching out to them for a month now. they don‚Äôt understand the magnitude of this, and how could they? if they‚Äôve never experienced what i have, what we have ‚Ä¶ i‚Äôve left my ex for 2 yrs now, yet his face still haunts me every day. his (now ex) girlfriend reached out to me 2 months ago to ask for help to leave him - she found my email address after most likely hacking into his account and finding all my emails of pain to him. and now she wants me to help her press charges against him - but i have no evidence, i don‚Äôt even have legal citizenship in the country they are now in. since she asked me of this a month ago, i have felt so paralyzed in what to do -- my gut instinct of helping her and also bringing him to justice ‚Ä¶ vs ‚Ä¶ my fear of him getting out unscathed and then going after her/myself and our loved ones. i am so overcome with guilt that i can‚Äôt focus on work (i‚Äôm so terribly far behind!), i can‚Äôt focus on anything unless i space out and watch tv shows ‚Ä¶ every night i have nightmares of him, only to wake up and have constant flashbacks of him ...

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
i never thought i‚Äôd have the strength to go public with my experience. i was told no one wanted to hear what happened. i was blamed for what happened. i lived for years in shame and silence.

then there came a time when i realized my voice was more powerful than my silence. from my voice, and the collective voice of survivors around the world, comes powerful change.

i‚Äôm honored to stand with these women who started the process of reform by sharing their experiences. i‚Äôm proud of all of us for breaking the silence, and we stand for those who cannot. 
#breakthesilence #metoo #enough #survivor @startribune

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
because i didn't. and that should be enough. but, clearly, these days, it still isn't enough. so i will tell you my "why". *caveat* i am sharing this not to be political because, let me be absolutely clear, i think we would be witnessing the same outrageous, unacceptable, politically-motivated mistreatment of a sexual assault survivor if this were a democratic president‚Äôs nominee with a democrat run judiciary committee. it would be the same. and that is the travesty. so here goes:
.
i didn't report because:
‚Ä¢i was a young woman in college who was far away from home.
‚Ä¢i was scared to death.
‚Ä¢i felt ashamed and dirty.
‚Ä¢i thought people would not believe me.
‚Ä¢i thought it was my fault.
‚Ä¢i didn't want people to look at me and whisper.
‚Ä¢i didn't want to relive it. over and over.
‚Ä¢i knew most women who do report do not get justice.
.
i didn't tell anyone for a long time because:
‚Ä¢it was my story and releasing it was the only thing i felt i had control of in my life.
‚Ä¢i was still ashamed.
‚Ä¢i had seen how other women were treated who told their story, and didn't want that response for my story.
‚Ä¢i chose not to. it was my body. my life. my choice.
.
today was hard for me and for so many other people. i listened to dr. ford's testimony with tears in my eyes. as she retold the story of probably the worst moment of her life it made me relive my own. it took great courage to do this. let me be clear about this.... there is almost no reason i would ever come forward and sit in front of strangers and tell my story and be open to questions about it. almost no reason. but i have to say that if the perpetrator of my sexual assault would be up for one of the most important jobs in our nation then i would absolutely muster up the courage because it would be the only right thing to do.
.
this is why i didn't report. this is why i have kept the truth quiet for decades. it is the same reason men and women who were molested by priests decades ago kept quiet. i just wish  my story (& others‚Äô) would be met with the same reaction as the priests‚Äô victims have been. silence does not negate truth. it proves trauma.
.
#whyididntreport #whiteboxlettering #metoo #metoomovement

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
after taking some sleeping pills, i have only one message. #bringbackourhumanity . all the things people ask for my counsel, my assistance and my intervention comes down to a very palpable lack of humanity. 
sexually molesting children, ritualistic killings,  sexual exploitation of teenage students, discrimination & social biases, religious misogyny are manifestations of our eroded sense of empathy and acts of kindness. 
certain acts just shouldn't be done, period. that's what makes us humans, setting us apart from predatory animals. 
back story: coming back from our office carnival, i witnessed someone being burnt alive at 5am today at rawdon street. bunch of people stood by and no one wanted to intervene. i called a police guy to do so and he said the man is dying soon. he just stood unmoved by my words. i was prevented from intervening by my tricycle (keke) driver who was adamant that i might be killed in the process of intervening. 
i'm still replaying it in my head and i feel so angry. üò≠üò≠üò≠üò≠üò≠üò≠üò≠ i'm stuck with the question of, is this really what we have come to? i'm not gonna talk about this anymore. i'm done.
